Source: alertnet.com, Reuters report, Tue 1 Mar 2005 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/HAN213142.htm>

Viet Nam: Another Human Case of Avian Influenza Virus Infection in the North
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
A 35-year-old poultry market cleaner in northern Viet Nam has
contracted avian influenza, which has killed 47 [42 as of 2 Feb 2005,
according to WHO] people in Asia, the Lao Dong newspaper reported on
Tue 1 Mar 2005
It said the woman was taken to hospital on Thu 24 Feb 2005, and tests
confirmed on Mon 28 Feb 2005 that she had contracted avian influenza
virus, which experts fear could mutate into a form that could pass
between people and unleash a global influenza pandemic that might
wipe out millions.
The woman, from a Hanoi district, is the latest bird flu patient
detected in northern Viet Nam, where fewer outbreaks have been
reported in recent weeks, but where the cool spring weather still
favours the spread of the H5N1 virus.
Officials said the virus killed a 69-year-old man last week and
infected another 2, all of them in the northern province of Thai
Binh, 110 km (70 miles) southeast of Hanoi and far from the southern
Mekong Delta where the outbreaks began in December. The 2 patients
have been treated in the same Hanoi hospital to which the latest
victim was taken.
Doctors there declined comment on their conditions, but state media
said one of the 2 from Thai Binh [province], a 21-year-old man, was
in critical condition and on a respirator after drinking duck blood
before the Lunar New Year festival last month. His 14-year-old
sister, suspected of having bird flu, is also being treated at the
Hanoi hospital. [It was reported that the girl had tested negative in
ProMED-mail post "Avian influenza, human - East Asia (38): Viet Nam
20050228.0629" - Mod.CP]
The H5N1 strain has killed 14 people in Viet Nam since December
[2004], taking the total in Asia to 47 since the virus erupted across
large parts of Asia at the end of 2003. Almost all the victims -- 34
Vietnamese, 12 Thais and a Cambodian -- have caught it directly from
poultry.
--
