[3]
Date: Tue 1 Mar 2005
From: David Ozonoff <dozonoff@bu.edu>
Source: Xinhuanet News Agency, Tue 1 Mar 2005 [edited]


Viet Nam: A Human Case of Avian Influenza under Treatment in Hanoi
------------------------------------------------------------------
An [unidentified] person from the Vietnamese capital of Hanoi, who is
under treatment in the city's Tropical Disease Institute, has just
been confirmed to have contracted avian influenza A (H5N1) virus
infection, raising the total number of infections in the country
since December 2004 to 21, local media reported Tue 1 Mar 2005
--
David Ozonoff, MD, MPH
Professor of Environmental Health
Department of Environmental Health
Boston University School of Public Health
715 Albany Street
Boston, MA 02118
<dozonoff@bu.edu>
[It is presumed that the patient referred to above is either the
36-year-old male or the 35-year-old female referred to in parts [1]
and [2], respectively. It is difficult to establish the precise
number of human cases of avian influenza that have been confirmed in
Viet Nam with certainty on account of the practice of identifying
cases by their age. Also the WHO data and the local data are computed
from different start dates. The number of deaths can be established
with more certainty. The WHO cumulative count has not been updated
since 2 Feb 2005, when the number of deaths was given as 42 (29 in
Viet Nam, 12 in Thailand and one in Cambodia)-- see
<http://www.who.int/csr/disease/avian_influenza/en/. According to the
Vietnamese authorities, the number of fatalities in Cambodia and
Thailand has remained the same at 1 and 12 respectively, whereas the
number of deaths in Viet Nam has risen from 29 to 34, making the
overall total 47 for East Asia as a whole. - Mod.CP]
